    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#boardman-hayes1973"/>, n. <citedRange>2239</citedRange> (ph., dr.)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>003500</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <w lemma="κοινός">κοινὸς</w> <persName type="divine" ref="#Demeter"><name nymRef="#Δαμάτηρ"><subst><del rend="corrected">Ο</del><add place="overstrike">Δ</add></subst><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">άματρι</supplied></name></persName>
                </ab>
                                </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p><app loc="1"><lem><subst><del rend="corrected">Ο</del><add place="overstrike">Δ</add></subst></lem> 
                    <rdg resp="#boardman-hayes1973">Δ</rdg>
                        <rdg resp="#boardman-hayes1973">O</rdg> <note>Boardman</note></app>
                </p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> en indivision avec D<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">èmèter</supplied> (?).</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> joint to D<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">emeter</supplied> (?).</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> in comune con D<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">emetra</supplied> (?).</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>As the last letter seems to be <foreign xml:lang="grc">Δ</foreign>, corrected from <foreign xml:lang="grc">O</foreign>, it is conceivable from 
                    the context of find that there was a phrase like <foreign xml:lang="grc">κοινὸς ἐὼν τῶι θεῶι</foreign> with Demeter's name; 
                    that formula is used about a man bound to a dedication, whose properties are considered jointly owned with a god even after his death (see 
                    <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr016700</ref>,  l. 58).</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
